{{rel-top|Etymology Theories}}
* The earliest written use of blizzard as a term to describe a severe snow storm, spelled "blizard" was in the [[W:Estherville, Iowa|Estherville, Iowa]], ''Northern Vindicator'' on 23 April 1870.  {{w|O.C. Bates|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=WM6qJuAnzq4C&pg=PA48&dq=%22snowstorm+an+Americanism%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=drLNVJCFDta2oQT34IGQBw&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=o.c.%20bates&f=false}} neologistic editor of The Northern Vindicator used it for the terrific snowstorms in the state that spring. He claimed he had picked up the term from a local character Lightning Ellis, on account of his violent out bursts. One week later it appeared again in the same newspaper, only with the now common double-z spelling.
:
* Blizzard possibly comes from the surname "Blizzard" dating back to 1700's(?). ''Blizzard'' surname possibly comes from the ''blizzard'' one, dating back to the 1500's(?).
:
* The word blizzard was used (not in relation to the weather) in America prior to 1870. It had various, loosely associated, now obsolete meanings: 
:  • {{w|Blast with a firearm or cannon|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=f2k3kgAACAAJ&dq=Davy+Crockett's+Almanack&hl=en&sa=X&ei=50HlVKeDE8G_ggTGqYDoDA&ved=0CAoQ6AEwAA }} (whether one or multiple bullets or pellets uncertain)
:  • {{w|Verbal blast|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=o51x5N-FZcoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=tour+down+east&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EETlVK_8Fsm6ggSDjoC4Aw&ved=0CBgQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=blizzard&f=false}}
:  • {{w|Blast with a firearm or cannon|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=et7WAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA129&dq=%22blizzard+american+a+word%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=D8XJVP3GOs21ogSi1YKoDA&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22blizzard%20american%20a%20word%22&f=false}} (single ball or bullet):
:  • {{w|Blazing fire|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=t-ksGlUTcagC&pg=PA153&dq=%22blizzard+of+my+soul%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_ZfMVILIDMm5ogTYxoKQDw&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22blizzard%20of%20my%20soul%22&f=false}}
:  • {{w|Heavy or painful physical blow|title=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83035487/1849-08-25/ed-1/seq-3/#date1=1836&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=blizzard&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=8&state=&date2=1869&proxtext=blizzard&y=12&x=19&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=5}} (not involving a firearm)
:  • {{w|Literal or figurative attack|title=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85033395/1851-07-29/ed-1/seq-3/#date1=1836&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=blizzards&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=1&state=&date2=1869&proxtext=blizzard&y=12&x=19&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=15}}
:  • {{w|Exclamation|title=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn86092163/1853-11-05/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1836&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=blizzards&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=15&state=&date2=1869&proxtext=blizzard&y=12&x=19&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=14}} (like “the blazes” or “blue blazes")
:  • {{w|Blast with multiple firearms or with a firearm loaded with multiple pellets|title=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84028820/1860-11-15/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1836&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=blizzard&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=6&state=&date2=1869&proxtext=blizzard&y=12&x=19&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=5}}
:  • {{w|Shot of liquor|title=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85054616/1870-09-21/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1869&sort=relevance&rows=20&words=blizzard+Blizzard&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=5&state=&date2=1870&proxtext=blizzard&y=15&x=19&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2}}
:
* Probably from the German {{term|blitzartig||lang=de|very fast, like  lightning}}
