* Another {{w|version|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=YbpZAAAAMAAJ&q=%22I+took+a+blizzard+at+one%22&dq=%22I+took+a+blizzard+at+one%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=v0fMVMndB8jToATd1oD4BQ&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAzgK}} suggests French blesser (to wound), but neither this nor the German can be substantiated. Yet another claims that blizzard derives from English dialect blizzer, meaning "a blaze" or "flash" ("Put towthry sticks on th' fire, an' let's have a blizzer," {{w|English Dialect Dictionary|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=oEMOAQAAMAAJ&pg=PR16&dq=%22English+Dialect+Society%22+Nottinghamshire&hl=en&sa=X&ei=SaTNVICRHYbioASAgIGADA&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=blizzer&f=false}}) or from blazer (something that blazes or blasts), which gave the early sense "a volley of firing guns," that is, a general "blazing away." 
:
* {{w|Thomas Ratcliffe of Worksop, Nottinghamshire, in the March 17, 1888, edition|title=[://books.google.com/books?id=9GECAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA217&dq=%22blizzer%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9MrJVJHZN8zeoASjmoCYCg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22blizzer%22&f=false]
}}
BLIZZARD (7th S. v. 106).—The word blizzard is well known through the Midlands, and its cognates are fairly numerous. I have known the word and its kin fully thirty years. Country folk use the word to denote blazing, blasting, blinding, dazzling, or stifling. One who has had to face a severe storm of snow, hail, rain, dust, or wind, would say on reaching shelter that he has "faced a blizzer," or that the storm was "a regular blizzard." A blinding flash of lightning would call forth the exclamation, "My! that wor a blizzomer!" or "That wor a blizzer!" "Put towthry sticks on th' fire, an let's have a blizzer"—a blaze. "A good blizzom" = a good blaze. "That tree is blizzared" = blasted, withered. As an oath the word is often used, and "May I be blizzerded" will be readily understood.
:
* A check of some of the Midlands regional glossaries printed in the 1800s finds several entries for blizzy. First, from Anne Baker, {{w|Glossary of Northamptonshire Words and Phrases |title=https://books.google.com/books?id=be8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA57&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=StrJVMTOGszzoAS6l4Jw&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false}}(1854):

BLIZZY. A blaze. "Blow the fire, and let's have a nice blizzy." This, though now considered a vulgarism, is a retention of the original A.-Sax. blysa, a blaze.

And Mrs. Parker, {{w|A Glossary of Words Used in Oxfordshire|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=iIAHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA114&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=StrJVMTOGszzoAS6l4Jw&ved=0CCEQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false}} (1876):

Blizzy, a flaring fire produced by putting on small sticks. Ex. 'Let's 'a a bit of a blizzy afore us goes to bed.'

And from Arthur Evans & Sebastian Evans, {{w|Leicestershire Words, Phrases, and Proverbs|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=3VAJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA106&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=StrJVMTOGszzoAS6l4Jw&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false}}(1881):

Blizzy, sb. a blaze. 'When the squoire, a coom anoigh, they joomped o' the blizzy an' douted it.' 

And from Barzillai Lowsley, {{w|A Glossary of Berkshire Words and Phrases|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=HKITAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA50&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-NnJVOiGK5TVoASR_IHYCA&ved=0CFUQ6AEwCg#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false}} (1888):

BLIZZY.— A blaze. The fire is said to be all of a "blizzy" when pieces of wood have been inserted amongst the coal to make it burn cheerfully. 

And from G. F. Northall, {{w|A Warwickshire Word-book|title=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zy4_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA31&dq=%22Blizzy%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-NnJVOiGK5TVoASR_IHYCA&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22Blizzy%22&f=false}} (1896):

Blizzy, sb. A blaze, a blast, a flare of fire. A.-Sax. blysa, a blaze. Common.

They suggest that blizzy survived from the ancient word blysa in numerous localities and might well share a root with the U.S. blizzard. 
